Tourism,wFZyNQAIcdE,UgzCkVkMsWrqizy4Wz14AaABAg,,@johncraven9719,"The subject seems a non-starter.

One might think that living or realising a dream would always give pleasure to someone. But buying a product without really asking the right questions is almost bound to lead to worries, anger, disappointment.
BTW one of life's principles is ""disappointment is the inevitable result of expecting too much"". Many would book a cheap hôtel in order to increase their holiday spending budget or because of their youthful enthusiasm, but would be stupid to complain about the lack of comfort or quiet!
Those who travel while constantly comparing things to ""how it was back home"" are also bound to become narrow-minded and dissatisfied. To voyage with a sense of curiosity and discovery is a better mindset.

Then again do you want sandy beaches, mountain lakes, hiking, total relaxing, a hired car, being part of a tourist guided group, alone, with someone special? Have you got travel within the country sorted out? Do you know what currency is used (e.g. not every member country of the European Union uses the Euro as currency!)",2026-05-03T22:38:41Z,2026-05-03T22:38:41Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-04T02:02:20.410485
Tourism,wFZyNQAIcdE,UgyJm3QJywYzn8Jev-d4AaABAg,,@missusd1130,"To avoid in Wisconsin: My home state: Events: The WI state fair, for much of the reasons stated here, also drinking events in Madison, for CRIME reasons, including being given knockout and rape drugs, esp. during Freak fest and the Mifflin street block party, and The Hodag Festival which turns out to be mostly a hidden Stugris drug, drunk, prostitute and hidden theft fest on hidden steroids.  If you want family friendly, county fairs are the way to go.  If you need something ""more exciting"", I suggest the Dells preferably out of the most active time--less expsneisve, less crowded, and way easier to schedule in the ""off season"" between mid August-mid June.  Yeah, avoid July visits.  Milwaukee should be avoided entirely unless you want to see things like the Betty Brin and other museums outside of crowded times.  Stay out of Milwaukee at night!  Don't park except in paid places, You car MIGHT be watched in those areas.  Most other places in WI are great including Door County, but look for a mosquito or tick report.  You'll thank me.  Biting flies can get guaranteed when those are active and some don't give a rip about DEET.  We've had a first hand experience of DEET failing to even affect ticks and biting flies, mine included a cases of Babiosis.  My recommendation, Visit in August through November to take advantage of the lovely foliage and harvest fest which can be quite family friendly and still have the brewskis you're wanting.  Easily Spring in great too, the bugs are still dead and the worst thing you'll experience is mud.  The camping is best in May and early June but in some places the ticks are out already.  August if ideal drying out and the sicks start to die out.  In SD where I live now stay away from Crazy Horse Monument.  It's not done and insanely expensive.  THey're right about Mt Rushmore, the parking is insanely expensive and don't visit on a cloudy day!  Buy a start park pass the SD state parks are all great, not just Custer and really worth visiting and has less ticks and mosquitoes than WI except during July  Outside of July and January/February and with a careful following of weather reports (because in May we get summer one day and winter the next LOL!).  If you're a cheapie, Spearfish anyone is FREE to explore!  And the city of Spearfish is a tourist paradise with not too far Rapids City having a lot of great sights, places to visit and even hiking areas that are great views and not hard to manage.",2026-05-03T20:39:29Z,2026-05-03T20:39:29Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-04T02:02:20.410491
