Tourism,wFZyNQAIcdE,UgxrzBelXQJPc2twMDR4AaABAg,,@mtnsidhe,"Having been to a number of these places, I don't agree with all of these assessments. For instance, travelers should always expect and protect themselves from pickpockets, especially in Europe.

Pisa should be a 2-hour stop between other places, and do climb to the top if you can. Avoid the toilets in the restaurants, they are literally a white-tiled hole in the floor.

Venice is just awful. Not only crowded, over priced, touristy and smelly, but also hot, muggy, and mosquito-infested. There are no screens on the windows and no AC, so sleeping at night requires open windows, and fat, blood-filled mosquitos in your room come morning. If you do go, be sure to see St. Mark's Square and Cathedral and feed the pigeons for a photo.


Versailles should be on this list. Long lines, huge entrance fee, shuffling through one enormous cube-shaped room after another, all filled with gilt-framed paintings and ostentatious rococco furniture and priceless gewgaws, all behind ropes, over and over and over until they all blur together. Lots of walking and standing in return for feeling simultanelously overwhelmed and underwhelmed, plus tired and bored. There is a separate tour for the gardens, which may have been better, but still, probably lots of walking, only in the sun.",2026-05-02T17:50:12Z,2026-05-02T22:50:12Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-04T02:02:20.410789
Tourism,wFZyNQAIcdE,UgxR0zVY0d5jfrVlihx4AaABAg,,@Twinturboh6,"Venezia is good, just busy from tourism obviously and like many of these places the REAL Italian food will never be next to or in Piazza San Marco or any other landmark. You have to go a few blocks away from that to get the good stuff. Definitely do not regret visiting.",2026-05-02T17:36:43Z,2026-05-02T17:36:43Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-04T02:02:20.410794
