AFCON,MU-oq7Nthp8,UgxQLQtNL68jHrAwsap4AaABAg,,@reginaldoklah6845,"The field of play doctrine means that the referee’s decision on the pitch is final, as long as he applies the laws and the spirit of the game.

In this case, the referee allowed the players to come back and finish the match. Once the game was completed, that decision should stand.

CAF’s Rule 82/83 talks about forfeiture, but a forfeiture only happens when a team clearly refuses to continue. Senegal did not refuse—they came back and played. So it is hard to say the match was forfeited.

The referee had the power to end the game and declare a forfeit if he wanted to, but he didn’t. Instead, he allowed the match to continue, and that decision is important.

Even players like Achraf Hakimi have accepted that Senegal won, which shows that on the field, the result was clear.

Arguments about yellow cards or poor refereeing are different. Those are just mistakes by the referee and usually do not change the final result of a match.

So overall, once the referee allowed the game to continue and finish, the result should not be overturned.",2026-03-22T13:13:32Z,2026-03-22T13:13:32Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-04T02:02:49.716242
